  "derivation_layer": {
    "source_latex": "% BEGIN TZP DERIVATION LAYER\n\\tzpsection{Derivation Layer}\n\\paragraph{Primary Equation.}\n\\begin{equation}\n\\langle O(x)O(0)\\rangle\n\\sim\n|x|^{-2+\\eta}.\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Exponent Dependence.}\n\\begin{equation}\n\\eta=\\eta(d_{\\mathrm{eff}},\\mathrm{TZP}).\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Primary Derivation.}\nAt a quantum critical point, correlation length diverges and the system loses a preferred length scale.  \nAn observable $O(x)$ therefore has a scale-free two-point function:\n\\begin{equation}\n\\langle O(x)O(0)\\rangle\n\\sim\n|x|^{-\\Delta}.\n\\end{equation}\n\nWith anomalous exponent $\\Delta=2-\\eta$, this becomes\n\\begin{equation}\n\\boxed{\n\\langle O(x)O(0)\\rangle\n\\sim\n|x|^{-2+\\eta}.\n}\n\\end{equation}\n\nIn the TRAWIN setting,\n\\begin{equation}\n\\eta=\\eta(d_{\\mathrm{eff}},\\mathrm{TZP}).\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Interpretation.}\nQuantum criticality is detected through power-law correlations whose exponents may depend on effective dimension and TZP deformation.\n% END TZP DERIVATION LAYER"
  },
